defaultThis paper will examine the factors that influence police mis-recording of crime, addressing the following themes in sequence:
defaultContextdefault2. In or
defaultder to appreciate the impact of current day police performance practices and resultant behaviour, it is necessary to understand the evolution and recent history of UK police performance management; what follows is a brief summary. 
default3. 
defaultThe roots of modern d
defaultay police performance management in the UK can be traced to the early 1980s, and 
defaultthe drive
default to demonstrate efficiency, economy and effectiveness. This heralded the beginning of a paradigmatic shift towards managerialism across the UK police service, which c
defaultame into being as part of wider public service reforms of the era, known as 
defaultNew Public Management (NPM). (See Hood, 1991, 
default1995, 
default1996, 1998; Pollitt and Bouckaert, 2000; Pollitt, 2002
default; Guilfoyle, 2012)
default4. 
defaultNPM-based practices intensified throughout t
defaulthe 1990s
default and into the 2000s. In 1994, t
defaulthe 
defaultPolice and Magistrates Cou
defaultrt Act (Home Office, 1994)
default conferred autho
defaultrity upon the Home Secretary to,
default “…to direct police authorities to es
defaulttablish levels of performance (‘
defaultperformance targets
default’
default) to be aimed at in seeking to ac
defaulthieve the objective”. (Home Office, 1994, p.16) 
defaultThis marked a shift toward centralised control through the application of targets, which came to characterise police performance management during subsequent years.
default5. 
defaultPost 1997
default, 
defaultNPM-orientated performance no
defaultrms were further consolidated through the vigorous application of
default performance indicators, numerical targets, 
default‘league tables’
default, audit and inspection, 
defaultand 
defaultthe holding to account of individuals for perceived ‘poor’ performance. (Loveday, 1998; 2005)
default As part of
default the 
default1998 Comprehensive Spending Review (CSR), 366 Public Service Agreements (PSAs) were introduced across the public sector, which included over 600 performance targets. (Chief S
defaultecretary to the Treasury, 1998a,
default 1998b; James, 2004)
default6. 
defaultThis was followed by the 
defaultPolice Reform Act of 2002 (Home Office, 2002), which 
defaultheralded
default a 
defaultfurther 
defaultintensification of NPM-based practices
default. (
defaultJones
default, 2
default003
default) The Act:
default“…provided the Home Secretary with powers to set national police priorities, remove chief office
defaultrs and directly intervene in the management of local police services”. (Loveday, 2006, p.284)
default7. 
defaultInterventionist tactics adopted by bodies set up
default to scrutinise forces
default (for example, the 
defaultPrime Minister’s Delivery Unit (PMDU)
default and
default the 
defaultPolice Standards Unit (PS
defaultU)
default)
default, 
defaultto assess
default performance against targets
default,
default and expose ‘poor performers’
default continued throughout the
default first decade of the 21
defaultst
default Century. 
default(Hood and Dixon, 2010)
default Forces were assessed against criteria set out within the new 
default‘Policing Performance Assessment 
defaultFramework’ (PPAF) (Home Office, 2005),
default 
defaultwhich was superseded by
default the 
default‘
defaultAssessment of Policing and Community Safety
default’
default framework (APACS), amongst others.
default 
default(Home Office, 2007)
default8. Following the abolition of APACS in 2010, government policy has moved away from centr
defaultally-imposed numerical targets, although they are still widely-applied within police forces, as well as by a number of PCCs. Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary
default (HMIC) also retains peer comparison
default methodology 
defaultthat is 
defaultbased on a ‘league table’ approa
defaultch, which ranks forces against each other. Therefore, despite this policy shift at the national level, the legacy of 
defaultNPM-orientated
default practices 
defaulthas helped perpetuate a
default dominant mode of performance management that is ingrained within the police psyche.
default9. 
defaultThis is the context within which gaming and other dysfunctional behaviour associated with police mis-recording of crime has occurred.
defaultPolice Performance Measurement and Its Prevailing Characteristicsdefault10. Effective performance measurement and management sys
defaulttems are necessary for multiple reasons. Davis (2012) emphasises:
default“Performance measures are a primary method of ensuring that the police are held accountable in democratic societies”. (
defaultDavis, 2012, 
defaultp.3)
default11. 
defaultEvidence of performance is necessary to ensure a
defaultc
defaultcountability and transparency
default, which is vital in fostering policy legit
defaultimacy.
default Using the right measures in the right way also helps managers understand how the system is performing, thereby enabling a cycle of continuous improvement. (See Deming, 1986, 1994
default)
default12. Due to the difficulty in quantifying outcomes in complex public service environments, police performance information has tended
default to focus on quantitative numerical dat
defaulta and is heavily reliant upon proxy measures. This carries significant risks when at
defaulttempting to assess performance, but is further hampered by common practices relating to how the data is routinely presented and used. Coupled with perverse incentives associated with numerical targets and league tables, these practices significantly increa
defaultse the likelihood of 
defaultgaming, such as in the case of crime being mis-reported. 
default13. 
defaultIn UK policing, there are three dominant components that contribute towards this risk. I refer to them as the ‘three pillars’ of traditional police performance management. T
defaulthey are:
default14. 
defaultTaken in isolation, each has the potential to 
defaultseverely distort activity, damaging service delivery and inadvertently encouraging dysfunctional responses. They will now be examined in turn.
defaultBinary Comparisonsdefault1
default5
default. The
default practice
default of making binary comparisons
default involves comparing two isolated numeric values, 
defaultthen interpreting the difference between them as though it were a trend. 
defaultSuch c
defaultomparisons are routinely made with
default 
defaultlast week, last month, last quarter, the average, the cumulative year-to-date figure, and so on. The outcome is that a single numeric value or
default percentage change is 
defaultpresente
defaultd as though it represents a confirmed trajectory within the data.
default1
default6
default. 
defaultThe following 
defaultexamples
default are typical:
default“…
defaultcrime has been reduced by 10% across the force area. This is 3,963 fewer victims of crime compared to the previous 12 
defaultmonths...” (North Yorkshire Police, 2013)
default“The number of house burglaries reported to police fell by 36 per cent during Operation Brightshadow, which ran from Monday, October 3 to Sunday, October 9, compared to the week before”. (Essex Police, 2013a)
default17.
default 
defaultB
defaultinary comparisons tend to be used because of their si
defaultmplicity. They appear to convey 
defaultinformation about ‘direction of travel’, and make for easy-to-consume quasi-statistical performance information. The danger of using them, however, is that they are 
defaulttoo
default si
defaultmplistic. 
defaultBird 
defaultet al
default (2005) warn that the
defaultir
default use encourage
defaults
default over-interpretation 
defaultof very minor changes amidst
default data, leading to false conclusions. They strongly caution against the practice, noting:
default“Very particularly the practice of concentrating on a compar
defaultison with the most recent value, this year’s results compared with last year’s, may be very misleading for reasons including regression to the mean”. (2005, p.14)
default18
default. 
defaultEssentially, the inadequacies associated with binary comparisons make the approach fundam
defaultentally incapable of conveying any useful information
default whatsoever
default.
default Despite this, the practice is probably the single most common method of presenting performance data in UK policing. 
defaultThe practice also invites
default unintended behavioural changes
default, which
default occur because assumptions about performance based on a binary comparison are often accompanied by implicit exhortations to improve. 
defaultA typical example would be where crime appears to have increased, when in fact data presented in a time series may indicate
default it is stable. Performance pressures associated with 
defaultsuch 
defaultan apparently increasing crime rate are one of the factors
default directly
default responsible for mis-recording of crime. 
defaultTabular Peer Comparisons (‘defaultLeague Tablesdefault’)default1
default9
default. 
defaultLeague tables form part of commonly-used a
defaultpproaches for assessing comparative performance, yet are vulnerable to methodological instabilities which undermine their efficacy; their use can also lead to unwarranted conclusions being drawn about performance, and act as an unintended catalyst for unhe
defaultalthy internalised competition and dysfunctional responses.
default (Jacobs and Goddard, 
default2007
default; Goldstein and Spiegelhalter, 1996; Bird 
defaultet al
default 2005)
default20
default. 
defaultTh
defaulte rationale behind 
defaulttheir application in policing
default 
defaultis outlined 
defaultas follows:
default“The intention is not to ‘set’ one 
defaultindividual force against another nor to use the performance indicators as a proxy for increasing inter-force competition, but rather to broaden the scope of management tools open to senior officers in the context of improving individual force performance”.
default (Barton and Beynon
default,
default 2011, p.363)
default2
default1. 
defaultNevertheless, the probability of gaming (such as 
defaultdeliberately under-recording crime) is heightened when league tables are used as a tool to compare peers.
default 
defaultHood (2007)
default, for example
default warns:
default“Like target systems, they are 
defaultlikely to produce output distortions as producers learn to find ways that move their organizations up the league tables in ways that do not reflect the intentions of those who framed the rankings, or ignore non-measured activities”. (
default2007, 
defaultp.101)
default22.
default 
defaultBehav
defaultioural changes are an inevitable consequence of league tables. When they are used in a performance environment alongside the expectation of continual crime reduction, the incentives and pressures integral to the league table approach can influence behaviou
defaultr to the extent that the 
defaultde facto
default purpose for activity becomes to avoid low league table rankings.
default2
default3
default. 
defaultDe Maillard and Savage (2012) note:
default“…the core rationale for police performance tables is more a reflection of a strategy of ‘naming and shaming’ - an 
defaultattempt to drive up performance by identifying the best and worst performing police organisations”. (2012, p.367)
default2
default4
default. Whilst the intention of policy makers would be that organisations are spurred on by these poor rankings to improve actual performance, the
default evidence points towards widespread gaming and other dysfunctional behaviour being induced as a direct consequence. (See Bevan and Hood, 2006; Hood, 2007; Rothstein 2008)
default It is suggested that the widespread practice of using league tables in UK police perf
defaultormance management is one of
default the contributory factors in
default case
defaults
default of police mis-recording of crime.
