defaultConclusion and Future Directiondefault3
default8
default. 
defaultF
defaultinally
default, whilst the dysfunctional practices outlined can be traced to these three pillars, 
defaultit is not my contention that performance management or measurement is a bad thing. It is absolutely necessary to measure 
defaultperformance in order to understand how the system is performing. Evidence of good performance fosters legitimacy and leads to organisational improvement through the sharing of good practice. S
defaultcrutiny of data
default is necessary to aid transparency and accountabil
defaultity. Additionally, there is a practical dimension to the collation and analysis of crime data, as it enables managers to interpret trends, understand anomalies and instigate an evidence-based response to confirmed patterns. 
default3
default9
default. 
defaultThe issue, however, is 
defaulthow
default 
defaultthis has largely been done in UK policing. The use of binary comparisons, league tables and numerical targets has 
defaultgenerated
default a legacy of performance management systems which are dominated by characteristics known to make accurate data 
defaultinterpretatio
defaultn impossi
defaultble
default, as well as
default drive dysfunctional and even unethical behaviours that work against the system and damage public confidence.
default40
default. 
defaultFor this reason, I propose the removal of all numerical targets from police performance frameworks; the only way
default to 
defaultsuccessfully
default 
defaultmitigate
default police
default mis-recording of crime statistics is to remove the incentive for doing so. 
defaultIt is also necessary to
default rethink 
defaultthe current use of league tables which attempt to neatly separate forces into ordered rankings, as well as the use of bi
defaultnary comparisons.
default 
default41
default. 
defaultAs an alternative, 
defaultI 
defaultendorse the adoption of Systems Thinking principles, and promote
default the 
defaultwider 
defaultuse of Statistical Process Control 
default(SPC) 
defaultcharts as a method for unders
defaulttanding crime data
default. This
default allows for 
defaultmuch more sophisticated
default data in
defaultterpretation
default and appreciation of systemic influences and interdependencies,
default 
defaultwhich
default should frame performance conversations at all levels.
default 
default4
default2
default. 
defaultThe removal of the 
defaulttriggers
default responsible for police mis-recording
default of crime 
defaultis the 
defaultonly 
defaultway to effectively 
defaultaddress 
defaultthe systemic latent conditions that incentivise the practice.
default 
defaultReplacing the blunt and counterproductive tools of traditional police performance management with SPC-based methodology has the potential to signal a paradigmatic shift that 
defaultsh
defaultould
default significantly
default 
defaultlimit
default gaming and dysfunctional behaviour, whilst signalling more mature and insightful performance management norms.
